<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900828-0017</DOCNO><DOCID>900828-0017.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>08/28/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   STOCKS AND BONDS soared and oil prices plummeted on theprospect of a peaceful solution to the Mideast crisis. TheDow Jones industrials leaped 78.71 points, this year'sbiggest gain, to 2611.63. Long-term Treasury bonds jumpedmore than 1 1/2 points, bringing their yield back under 9%.Crude prices sank as much as $4 a barrel, their sharpest dropon record. Early Tuesday in Vienna, OPEC ministerstentatively endorsed some members' moves to boost output.   ---</LP><TEXT>   Gold prices plunged about $27 an ounce in their sharpestone-day decline in more than seven years. Silver and platinumprices also sank. The recent Persian Gulf turmoil hasgenerated only a modest increase in investor interest in goldin the U.S.   ---   Tokyo stocks posted strong gains amid a firmer yen, ahealthier bond market and an absence of bad Mideast news. TheNikkei index jumped 976 points Monday to 25141.76, then rosea further 518.52 Tuesday morning.   ---   Many banks tightened their lending standards further inrecent months, largely out of concern over the economy andthe state of certain industries, a Fed survey found.Medium-sized firms felt the worst pinch. The report couldhelp support an easing by the Fed of interest rates.   ---   Consumer spending grew 0.5% in July, as personal incomerose 0.6%. But fears about the economy may restrain purchasesin the months ahead.   ---   A tobacco antitrust award against Brown andamp; Williamson wasoverturned. Brooke Group, formerly Liggett, had won the$148.8 million verdict.   ---   Former Guinness PLC Chairman Ernest Saunders was convictedof conspiring to inflate the firm's stock price to help its$4.91 billion bid to take over Distillers Co. in 1986. Threeco-defendants were also convicted in the case, which couldboost the reputation of British financial regulators.   ---   An insider-trading ruling that the government claims couldhinder prosecutions will get a rare review by a full federalappeals court.   ---   Stock buy-back programs are being launched or extended bymany companies that hope to snatch their own shares atbargain prices.   ---   Investors seeking arbitration of disputes with brokerswill have to pay higher fees to launch their claims. The NASDhas already imposed the increases, and the Big Board isexpected to follow suit within weeks.   ---   General Motors plans to triple the number of itsU.S.-built cars with air bags as standard equipment. GM hastrailed its U.S. rivals in this area.   ---   Merrill Lynch will get $17.5 million from its insurersunder a settlement of suits brought by the firm'sshareholders on its behalf. The case involved trading andinvestment losses.   ---   Tracor Holdings proposed to restructure $730 million ofits debt and said it may seek protection from creditors ifthe plan isn't approved.   ---   The IMF may lend more money to Brazil and other developingnations that import oil, a Treasury aide said.   ---   General Cinema posted a 78% drop in profit for the quarterthat ended in July. The theater operator and retailer citedlower movie attendance and reduced interest income.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 160,150,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2611.63, up 78.71; transportation 908.03, up 38.32; utilities194.42, up 3.46.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Brothers Treasury index 3326.27, up48.63.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 134.16, off 1.68;spot index 132.23, off 1.95.   Dollar: 144.25 yen, off 2.45; 1.5510 marks, off 0.0095.</TEXT></DOC>